@inv0ke it depends on the proving error. Often it's just a failing assertion that you added, you can debug that by adding a custom assertion message. Sometimes (I think in the cases above), it's a discrepancy between running the code outside / inside the prover. That case is indicated by the stack trace containing "checkPublicInput". It can happen if some of the inputs you use change every time you run the contract -- make sure running your contract methods is "idempotent", i.e. they can be run any number of times without changing the result and without having side-effects

^ in my case @gregor my actual instance method is wrapped with a decorator that ensures any side effects are reset back to the original state after running. This way i can remove side effects created at tx callback and also side effects at proving. no matter how many times my method runs
